<Layout title="Oncology & Palliative Assessment Tools" description="Oncology and palliative care assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Oncology &amp; Palliative</div>
  <h1>Oncology &amp; Palliative Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Performance status scales, symptom assessment tools, and prognostic instruments for oncology and end-of-life care.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>ECOG Performance Status</strong> — Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group 5-level functional status: 0 (fully active) to 4 (completely disabled). Primary eligibility criterion for clinical trials and treatment decisions.</li>
      <li><strong>Karnofsky Performance Scale (KPS)</strong> — 100-point functional status scale in 10-point decrements from 100 (normal, no complaints) to 0 (dead). Predicts treatment tolerance and prognosis in oncology.</li>
      <li><strong>WHO Performance Status</strong> — Five-level scale equivalent to ECOG; used interchangeably for functional status assessment in oncology patients.</li>
      <li><strong>Distress Thermometer</strong> — Single-item 0–10 distress visual analog scale plus 39-item problem checklist for cancer patients. Score ≥4 triggers psychosocial evaluation.</li>
      <li><strong>ESAS / ESAS-r (Edmonton Symptom Assessment System)</strong> — Nine or ten symptom visual analog scales: pain, tiredness, nausea, depression, anxiety, drowsiness, appetite, wellbeing, dyspnea, and other. Used in palliative care monitoring.</li>
      <li><strong>PPS (Palliative Performance Scale)</strong> — Ten-level functional performance scale (10–100%) for palliative patients based on ambulation, activity, self-care, intake, and consciousness. Predicts survival.</li>
      <li><strong>PPI (Palliative Prognostic Index)</strong> — Six-variable prognostic tool: PPS, oral intake, edema, dyspnea at rest, delirium, and weight loss. Score &gt;6 predicts &lt;3-week survival.</li>
      <li><strong>PaP Score (Palliative Prognostic Score)</strong> — Six-variable 30-day mortality prediction: dyspnea, anorexia, KPS, clinical prediction of survival, total WBC, lymphocyte percentage.</li>
      <li><strong>MASCC Score (Febrile Neutropenia)</strong> — Multinational Association for Supportive Care in Cancer score for low-risk febrile neutropenia: burden of illness, hypotension, COPD, solid vs. hematologic tumor, dehydration, inpatient/outpatient status, age. Score ≥21 = low risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Mucositis Grading (NCI-CTCAE)</strong> — Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events oral mucositis grading 1–5 from asymptomatic changes (Grade 1) to life-threatening consequences (Grade 4) and death (Grade 5).</li>
      <li><strong>CINV Risk Assessment</strong> — Chemotherapy-induced nausea/vomiting risk stratification: highly emetogenic (&gt;90%), moderately emetogenic (30–90%), low emetogenic (10–30%), minimally emetogenic (&lt;10%); guides antiemetic prophylaxis.</li>
      <li><strong>Hand-Foot Syndrome Grading</strong> — NCI-CTCAE 1–3 grading of palmar-plantar erythrodysesthesia from minimal symptoms (Grade 1) to severe blistering/ulceration limiting self-care (Grade 3).</li>
      <li><strong>Neutropenic Precautions Assessment</strong> — Structured evaluation of infection risk in neutropenia: ANC threshold, fever criteria, institutional protocols, and patient education documentation.</li>
      <li><strong>Hickman/Port Site Assessment</strong> — Structured evaluation of central venous access device exit site or port: site inspection, skin integrity, securement, patency, and signs of infection or thrombosis.</li>
      <li><strong>FAST Scale</strong> — Functional Assessment Staging: used in both dementia and palliative contexts to track progressive functional loss and inform hospice eligibility.</li>
      <li><strong>NEST (Needs at End of Life Screening Tool)</strong> — 13-item screen addressing physical, psychosocial, spiritual, and support needs of patients approaching end of life.</li>
      <li><strong>SUPPORT Prognostic Model</strong> — Study to Understand Prognoses and Preferences for Outcomes and Risks of Treatment; validated survival prediction model informing goals-of-care conversations.</li>
      <li><strong>Dyspnea in Dying Scale</strong> — Structured assessment of dyspnea severity and distress at end of life; guides palliative opioid and anxiolytic dosing for symptom management.</li>
      <li><strong>Comfort Care Assessment</strong> — Holistic patient and family assessment of physical comfort, psychosocial support, spiritual care, and bereavement preparedness in end-of-life care settings.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
